Blackduck Schools will be providing curbside pickup (breakfast & lunch) beginning Tuesday, September 8th. post_text:
Drakes speed and strength program is up and running. Any students grades 7-12 are welcome to participate in our summer workouts free of charge. We will be focusing on speed, agility, and strength as well as sport specific skills. We will run two groups, both in the main gym, on Mondays, Tuesdays, Thursdays, and Fridays. One group will go from 6am - 7am and one group 5pm - 7pm. Program will run until August 7th.

**Your health and safety is our number one priority, therefore we have the following guidelines in place.
-Please come dressed in practice clothes and bring a water bottle as the locker room & water fountains will be unavailable.
-We are to enter and exit through door # 3 only when we get into the gym
-Use your best judgement & stay home if you are experiencing any symptoms of illness.
Guidelines will be followed strictly to do our best in keeping everyone healthy. Hope to see you there! Spread the word.
GO DRAKES!

post_text:
Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT)

Minnesota is now offering funds for families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals, but not SNAP or MFIP. These families are urged to apply for this new program, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), it will provide up to $325 per child that families can use to purchase nutritious food for their household. Approximately 350,000 Minnesota children could benefit.

Learn more at: www.mn.p-ebt.org or contact the P-EBT hotline to find out more: 651-431-4050 or 800-657-3698.

FRENZEL AND BLOOM ARE STUDENTS OF THE WEEK

Junior high math teacher LeAnn Bolhuis selected 8th grader Bryce Frenzel as this week‚Äôs BHS Student of the Week for his work in Algebra. ‚ÄúBryce has impressed me on so many levels,‚Äù said Bolhuis. ‚ÄúHe does amazing academically, he has drive and motivation to do his very best‚Äîbut also Bryce gets along with everyone, He is sincerely kind to everyone. Even when I thought he was being mean and I was getting ready to yell at him he was actually being nice. It makes me laugh still when I think back to it. I heard Bryce say, ‚Äúdo you know what I hate about women?‚Äù This is where I was getting ready to yell, then he ended with. ‚Äúhow they are so under-appreciated.‚Äù
6th grader Isabella Bloom was chosen as the Blackduck Elementary Student of the Week by her teacher Danielle McKeeman. ‚ÄúIsabella inspired me this year,‚Äù said McKeeman. ‚ÄúShe seems to be fearless and tries most anything with a good attitude. She is a writer, an actor, a comedian, and a humanitarian. Bella is hard-working, thoughtful, and is always handing out compliments.

Thursday, May 28 - DROP-OFF DAY

Students are requested to return any school-owned materials on Thursday, May 28, any time between 7:00am and 7:00pm.

Please return any school property you have:

Textbooks & workbooks

Library books

Band instruments

Chromebooks, bags & chargers

Calculators

And anything else that belongs in school. If you are not sure, bring it and the teachers will let you know.

Directions: You can drive up to the curb on the west side of the school on 1st Street NE (by the HS gym). Please do not leave your vehicle. A teacher will come out to collect the materials then you will be on your way. Have a great summer and stay safe!

May 12, 2020

Dear Parent/Guardian of a Senior Student:

The Graduation Ceremony will take place on Friday, May 29, at 9:00 p.m. on the south side of the school. Parents will park in the student parking lot. One passenger vehicle will be allowed per household. You must remain in your vehicles for the entire program.

On Friday, May 22, students will be coming to the school to pick up their caps, tassels, stoles, and gowns and return textbooks and chromebooks. They will also draw a number for a parking spot. Students with 2 households need to call the high school office by Friday, May 15th, to receive a second parking spot.

Mark Lundin
High School Principal

MACKEY AND JUELSON ARE STUDENTS OF THE WEEK

Junior high math teacher LeAnn Bolhuis has selected 7th grader Alex Mackey as the high school student of the week for his work in Pre-Algebra. ‚ÄúAlex is such a goofy, fun kid. I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôve ever seen a frown on his face that wasn‚Äôt a joke,‚Äù said Mrs. Bolhuis. ‚ÄúHe talks to everyone and has no bias about who you are. Everyone in the school knows him and from the people I talk to I‚Äôve never heard a bad word about him. He brightens people‚Äôs day. I hope he always keeps his cheerful attitude. we definitely need more of it!
The Blackduck Elementary Student of the Week is 3rd grader Wyatt Juelson, who was chosen by his teacher, Jan Jason. ‚ÄúWyatt is a hard-working student who wants to do his best,‚Äù said Mrs. Jason. ‚ÄúHe enjoys reading and sharing his books with myself and others. We have also been doing PowerPoints and he really does a great job of presenting them. He is well-liked by his peers and enjoys school.‚Äù

SPEAKER OF THE WEEK

Haley Patel is this week‚Äôs Speaker of the Week. Haley is one of the most successful speakers for BHS, having advanced to the MSHSL State Tournament when she was in 8th grade. She is off to a great start in her sophomore season, competing in the category of Great Speeches. In Great Speeches a speaker takes a speech done at any point in history and combines excerpts from that speech with an original analysis of the historical and rhetorical significance of the speech as well as its current relevance. This season, Haley is analyzing Mahatma Gandhi‚Äôs Salt March Speech, and she has consistently placed in all of the varsity tournaments the team has competed in.

post_text: Miss Reese‚Äôs 1st graders experienced a mini building lesson in Mr. Berg‚Äôs classroom. With help from Mr. Berg, Mr. Tuey, and Blackduck 8th graders, each student built their very own tool box to bring home. The first graders were very proud of what they made and how much they learned. FRENZEL IS SPEAKER OF THE WEEK

Junior Regan Frenzel is this week‚Äôs Speaker of the Week. Regan has been a member of the Drakes speech team since 7th grade and is really on fire looking better than ever and coaches are expecting a top-notch season for her. Regan has competed in several categories of speech over the years and is this year in the category of Informative Speaking with an original speech entitled ‚ÄúNew World Architects.‚Äù Her speech shares some of the amazing ways in which ordinary people and scientists alike are finding ways to take plastic and rubber waste out of oceans, lakes, and landfills and use them to create things that are functional, beautiful, and serve the purpose of eliminating waste through their efforts and minimizing future waste because of them. Regan was the tournament champion at Hibbing last week and is looking good as we head into the heart of the season.

post_text:
DRAKES START JUNIOR HIGH SEASON
By Jennifer Parker

Blackduck hosted the first junior high speech tournament of the season on Monday night with 13 schools in attendance to kick off the season. Participating schools were Bemidji, Blackduck, Cass Lake-Bena, Fosston-Bagley, Grand Rapids, Laporte, Park Rapids, Pequot Lakes, Pillager, Pine River, Roseau, Trek North, and Walker.
The Drakes junior high team is 12 strong this season and they made a great first tournament showing with freshman Maia Tjepkes winning a tournament championship in the category of Serious Prose. Preston Zanter took 2nd place in Serious Drama, and several speakers placed 3rd in their categories, including: Ben Vezina in Creative Expression, Emma Frenzel in Serious Drama, Kaden Freeman in Informative Speaking, and Garrett Larson in Serious Prose.
The junior high speakers‚Äîwhile also members of the varsity team‚Äîcompete in a 5-tournament junior high conference which began Monday and continues on Tuesday in Cass Lake.

8 DRAKES SPEAKERS PLACE IN TOURNAMENT

Eight members of the Blackduck Drakes speech team placed in the Grand Rapids Varsity Tournament on Tuesday night that had been rescheduled due to stormy weather on January 18th. Earning red ribbons with superior ratings for Blackduck were Kaydre Gullette and Rachel Roberts in Duo Interpretation; Kaydre Gullette in Extemporaneous Reading; Haley Patel in Great Speeches; and Karly Pitzl in Storytelling. Four speakers earned honorable mention awards as well‚ÄîAllie Stark in Serious Interpretation of Poetry and three in the category of Serious Interpretation of Drama: Jastyn Rodgers, Preston Zanter, and Emma Frenzel.
The Drakes host the first junior high tournament of the season on Monday at Blackduck High School.

GULLETTE IS DRAKES SPEAKER OF THE WEEK

Junior captain, Kaydre Gullette, is this week‚Äôs Speaker of the Week. Kaydre is a five year member of Drakes varsity speech and has been a consistent winner all five years in the category of Extemporaneous Reading and has often done well when double-entering in both Prose and Duo. This year, Duo is her primary category with partner Rachel Roberts and their speech: ‚ÄúTen Easy Steps to Humiliation,‚Äù a comedic piece with a powerful message for young women. She is also competing in Extemp Reading with the book, ‚ÄúAll the Light We Cannot See.‚Äù She placed in Duo in the first tournament of the season and in both Duo and Extemp Reading in the second. It promises to be another very successful season for her!

Supervisor: James Bettin
Contact Person: Ryan Grow
Phone: 835-5206

Wednesday Night Volleyball is open to anyone 18 years of age and older and has graduated from high school. Please arrive before 7:00pm for warm-up and team selection. Please wear clean gym shoes, not street shoes! Please pay fees to the supervisor each night. Volleyball is cancelled when school is not in session or if school is let out early. Please fill out the registration form completely along with the insurance and liability waiver on the back of this form; you will not be allowed to participate if the waiver isn‚Äôt signed. No kids are allowed to be brought to this activity for liability purposes.

post_text:
BENEFIT FOR THE HASSEL FAMILY

There will be a benefit at The Pond in Blackduck for the Hassel family who are still recovering from a serious house fire in August. The benefit will be held on Saturday, October 26th from 4:00 to 8:00 p.m. at The Pond and the entire community is invited to come and share their support for a family who are also an important part of the Blackduck community. Renee Hassel is a personal banker at Deerwood in Blackduck as well as working part-time at The Pond and James is a longtime employee of Northwoods Lumber in Blackduck. All three of the Hassel kids, Layne, Nevaeh and Alayna are actively involved in many activities in the school and community.
There will be food, raffles, a silent auction, and much more. Please come out and show your support to help the Hassels get through this time of need. The meal is a free will donation and the bar will be open for drinks as well.
The Pond is also hosting a Halloween Party after the benefit with the Acoust Hicks, so plan to stick around and enjoy the fun!

BENEFIT FOR XAYVION RODGERS PLANNED

The Blackduck Wrestling Club is sponsoring a benefit for Xayvion Rodgers to help defray the medical costs accrued as a result of a terrible car accident on August 4th that caused serious injury to Rodgers and left him in a coma for two weeks with brain trauma. He spent several more weeks in the ICU in Fargo before finally being released.

The event will be held at in the Blackduck High School Multi-Purpose Room on Sunday, October 27th from 4:00-7:30 p.m. with a spaghetti meal for free will donations. There will also be a silent auction, bucket raffle, and possible live auction items as well.

Anyone who is interested in donating items can drop them off with Tammy Frenzel in the high school office or contact Laurie Reiplinger at 218-556-7530 or Julie Juelson at 218-766-7416. Everyone is encouraged to attend and show your support for Xayvion and his family!

Students in 4th, 5th, and 6th grade went on a field trip to Bemidji State Park last week. The field trip included biking, scavenger hunts, and a bike ride. The bike ride took students through Bemidji State Park and along Bass Lake. Smaller groups even biked to the Mississippi River along Lake Bemidji.

Students have been training during physical education class since the start of school on bike safety, handling, and communication skills. We had excellent weather and the students had a wonderful time. Mr. Gross would like to thank all of the bus drivers, paraprofessionals, teachers, and administration for making this field trip possible.

Here are some pictures from the trip!

GERMAN STUDENTS ENJOY SCHULTUTE
By Jennifer Parker

Frau Kari Slindee, BHS German teacher treated her students to the tradition of the Sch√ºlt√ºte last week. The Sch√ºlt√ºte is a custom that began more than 100 years ago to help ease the transition of children to the first day of school. Large cones were filled by the parents and given to the teacher prior to the first day to help children over their nerves and to give them both necessary and fun treats to help them enjoy the transition as well. The cones contained candy, pencils, erasers, stickers, fruit, and other items. The tradition continues to this day, and Frau Slindee gave her German students a taste of the tradition with small gifts in cones‚Äîmany of which she purchased while in Germany over the summer.
